- ( Callback Functions ):

- function passed as an argument to another function


( Example ):


let age = undefined;  //Variable to be modified


function UserAdd( x, y ){ return x + y; } // Returns a ADD result
function UserMultiply( x, y ){ return x * y; } // Returns a Multiplication result
function UserOutput( x ){ console.log(x); } // Outputs whatever value is passed in parameters


function UserTest( x, y, My1stCallback, My2ndCallback, My3rdCallback ){ 

 age = My1stCallback( x, y ); // Modifies age value ( 1st Calculation ) 

 My3rdCallback( age ); // Outputs age value ( of the 1st Calculation ), Output: 15

 age = My2ndCallback( x, y ); // Modifies age value ( 2nd Calculation ) 

}


UserTest( 5, 10, UserAdd, UserMultiply, UserOutput );
/* 
Function Call & Passing in Values: 
x = 5
y = 10
My1stCallback = UserAdd
My2ndCallback = UserMultiply
My3rdCallback = UserOutput
*/


console.log( "\n" + age ); // Last Output, Outputs age value ( of the 2nd Calculation ), Output: 50



- ( Function Expressions ):

- define functions as values or variables

( Example ):

const hello = function(x,y){ console.log(x + y); } // Variable into function

hello(10,20); // Outpus: 30



- ( Arrow Functions ):

- a concise way to write function expressions

( Example ):

// Removing the "function word"
const hello = (x,y) => { console.log(x + y); } 

// If Single statement, you can remove Brackets "{ }" 
const hello = (x,y) => console.log(x + y); 

hello(10,20); // Outpus: 30 ( the same )



- ( Closures ):

- functions that can access values 
  outside their own curly braces "{ }"

- it's a function combined w/ its Outer State 
  ( Outer State = Variables / Data defined outside a Function / Method )

- they require more memory & processing power


( Example (1) Simple example of closure  ):

let b = 3; // Variable accessed by the function, in Reference

function SampleADD(a){ return a + b; } 
// Calculates: 
// Value passed on the "a"( parameter ) & the "b" ( reference, which is 3 )
// Then Returns the Value


